Forest Fires In Brazil - A Time Series Data Analysis¶

By Arun James and Jonathan Cyriac

Introduction¶

Brazil is the largest country in Latin America with 3.2 million square miles of land and populated by approximately 208 million people. About 60% of this vast and diverse country holds part of the Amazon Rainforest. The Amazon is the world's largest tropical forest and of the part in Brazil, comprises abotu 1/3 of the world's remaining rainforests. It is home to over 56,000 identified plants, 1700 bird species, 695 unique amphibians, 578 mammals and 651 reptiles species. The Amazon Basin also possess an assortment of vegetation like rainforests, seasonal forests, deciduous forests, flooded forests and savannas.

Sadly, a mix of environmental and human factors have contributed to a massive amount of deforestation. It has torrential rain and almost never burns on its own, but when it burns, the blazes burn for weeks. It grows so intense that smoke is sent all the way to So Paulo, Brazil's largest city.

Forest fires are a serious problem for the preservation of the tropical forests. In order to maintain the environment, protect the species that already inhabit the Amazon, and preserve the area for future generations to experience and enjoy. We aim to understand the frequency and patterns of forest fires in a time series that can help to take action to prevent them.

  • The Forest Fire dataset can be found at Kaggle, at the following Link: https://www.kaggle.com/gustavomodelli/forest-fires-in-brazil
  • The Rainfall dataset can be found on Kaggle: https://www.kaggle.com/fabiopotsch/precipitation-in-brazil
  • The Agriculture dataset can be found on Data World: https://data.world/hdx/39056c79-3267-42d3-98cd-595ac6d91578

Modern Yearly Analysis¶

The graphs show a higher final count for fires compared to the first year in 1998, for the number of wildfires which occur in the Brazil. The data suprisingly doesn't have a perfect positive regression, but the total counts of incidents are increasing and it is more evident in a recent data mine conducted by the National Institue of Space Research (INPE) which released an infographic showing how many wildfires have become as a result of natural and human causes. The dataset we are using to extrapolate information about forest fires only covers until 2017, but the infographic is able to fill in the remaining data to make the data up to date to the current year we are interpreting the data. In the article, data journalist, Nial McCarthy, illustrates the significant increase in forest fires from January to August of 2019 compared to the previous year.

Year Analysis¶

Brazilian Fire Practices¶

The infographic above illustrates the increased rate of forest fires affecting the Brazilian part of the Amazon Basin. The article states that unsafe deforestation practices, carried out by the new Brazilian president, Jair Bolsonaro, and the dry arid environments has only increased the susceptibilty for the area to catch more violent and disastrous wildfires in response to multiple occurrences of fire suppression techniques. The negative side effect to the fire suppression techniques is that to efficiently and quickly get rid of the fire and prevent it from spreading, firefighters and units resort to using water and dry chemicals which ruin the land and slowly opens the same land to more problems in the future including inhabitability for animals and species but also the inability to use the land for resources including agriculture.

Source: Record Number Of Wildfires Burning In The Amazon:https://www.statista.com/chart/19089/number-of-wildfires-recorded-in-brazils-amazon-rainforest/

Year Analysis¶

CO2 Emissions Increase¶

As a result of these forest burnings, the environment is negatively impacted and thus logically will result in higher temperatures as a byproduct of the CO2 gas emissions from the burning wood. According to Dr. Werner Kurz from the NRC, forest fire CO2 emissions alone are released 2-3 more times the amount of fossil fuels byproducts. The negative effect of this is that the climate and environment will increase and make the land more difficult to reuse and later regrow. He continues to talk about how living trees are the reason why we aren't suffering from an overabundance of CO2 on Earth and burning the trees goes in the opposite direction by moving away from the long-term health of the planet.

Source: How do CO2 emissions from forest fires compare to those from fossil fuels?:https://www.cbc.ca/radio/quirks/sept-15-2018-summer-science-camping-under-a-volcano-plastic-in-beluga-bellies-and-more-1.4821942/how-do-co2-emissions-from-forest-fires-compare-to-those-from-fossil-fuels-1.4821944

Month Analysis¶

Peak Fires and Surprising Twist¶

The data proves the first half of the year there is a significant drop in the average number of forest fires that occur. The data also indicates the summer months have a huge spike in the number of fire cases and the main reason is because forest fires are easier to occur in dry, arid temperatures. The Amazon's location is very unique. The location has been able to support so many different species in its vast biome, and still protect its natural habitats from the high tempreatures from being located near the equator. The relative distance from the Earth's midline has statistically proven to generally have higher temperatures compared to other places. This detail, along with the magnitude of the summer heat, makes the Brazilian part of the Amazon vulnerable to forest fire incidents.

The strange pattern near the end of the year, analyzed by Dr. Derek Arndt, Chief of the Monitoring Division at the National Centers for Environmental Information, says the sudden increase in the number of cases in October and November is understood to be caused by failure for fall showers to wet the land and settle the arid temperatures. When this is combined with the windy atmosphere, the land becomes even more dry.

Source Why Does California Have So Many Wildfires?:https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/09/climate/why-california-fires.html

State Analysis¶

Analyzing the Extreme Cases¶

Sergipe is the lowest with Distrito Federal because they are two states in Brazil which are on the opposite side of the Amazon Rainforest. Since the data in the graphs above include states not in the rainforest, forest fires are assumed to be relatively low. Mato Grosso has one of the largest averages because it the largest state which also contains parts of the Amazon. Sao Paulo is the largest because as a capital, there are more people concentrated in it, which increases the risk of human caused forest fires.

Linear Regression¶

Using the data from precipitation data and the frequency of forest fires, we can predict future statistics of forest fires and have fire protection engineers prepare and work on preventative measures.

In [28]:
#X,Y = make_regression(n_samples = 100, n_features=2, noise=0.1)
x = np.array(data['year']).reshape(-1,1) 
y = data['number']
model = linear_model.LinearRegression()
model.fit(x,y)
coef = model.coef_
print('Regression Equation = ' + str(coef) + 'a + ' 'b')
print('R^2 Value = ' + str(model.score(x,y)))

Regression Equation = [2.16492433]a + b
R^2 Value = 0.004251116476173822
In [29]:
predictions = model.predict(x)
plt3 = sns.residplot(y.values, predictions,color = "green",scatter_kws={'s':6} ).set_title("Residuals")

The graph is showing multiple trends because it doesn't follow any other datasets. Integrating local Brazil temperatures and other categories which were discussed earlier will allow for stricter predictions.

Conclusion¶

Using the information from the previous graphs and the different time length analyses, the general trends point to finding preventative measures during the hot summer months and also targeting

According to the data, the prime times for forest fires are late June to August.

Need to watch out for when the rainfalls levels are low during October to early December. We can use a linear regression to predict when to increase the preventative measures in the area with the incerased potential to have a fire.
